vin至少有1个儿子。"},"hr":{"Abt 1305–":"oko 1305.–preminula","1300–Male":"1300–preminuo","1325–Male":"1325–preminuo","1305–Female":"1305–preminula","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","Abt 1325":"oko 1325.","Abt 1305":"oko 1305.","Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Engleska, United Kingdom","Of Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"Abt 1305–":"okolo 1305–Zesnulá","1300–Male":"1300–Zesnulý","1325–Male":"1325–Zesnulý","1305–Female":"1305–Zesnulá","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","Abt 1325":"okolo 1325","Abt 1305":"okolo 1305","Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","Of Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"Abt 1305–":"omkring 1305–Afdød","1300–Male":"1300–Afdød","1325–Male":"1325–Afdød","1305–Female":"1305–Afdød","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","Abt 1325":"omkring 1325","Abt 1305":"omkring 1305","Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Of Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1305–":"circa 1305–Overleden","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","1325–Male":"1325–Overleden","1305–Female":"1305–Overleden","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","Abt 1325":"circa 1325","Abt 1305":"circa 1305","Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Of Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1305–":"about 1305–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1325–Male":"1325–Deceased","1305–Female":"1305–Deceased","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","Abt 1325":"about 1325","Abt 1305":"about 1305","Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Of Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Richard Fitzstevin was born about 1305, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Richard Fitzstevin."},"et":{"Abt 1305–":"umbes 1305–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","Abt 1325":"umbes 1325","Abt 1305":"umbes 1305","Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1305–":"noin 1305–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1325–Male":"1325–Kuollut","1305–Female":"1305–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","Abt 1325":"noin 1325","Abt 1305":"noin 1305","Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Of Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1305